[[Category:Bahá'í gardens|Ridvan]]

{{short description|An ocean that existed in the late Neoproterozoic and early Paleozoic eras}} [[Image:Positions_of_ancient_continents,_550_million_years_ago.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Reconstruction of how the Iapetus Ocean and surrounding continents might have been arranged during the late [[Ediacaran]] [[period (geology)|period]]]] The '''Iapetus Ocean'''<ref>{{IPAc-en|aɪ|ˈ|æ|p|ɪ|t|ə|s}} {{cite web|url=http://phonetic-blog.blogspot.com/2010/04/iapetus-and-tonotopy.html|title=Iapetus and tonotopy|last=Wells|first=John|authorlink=John C. Wells|date=14 April 2010|accessdate=21 April 2010|work=John Wells's phonetic blog}}</ref> was an [[ocean]] that existed in the late [[Neoproterozoic]] and early [[Paleozoic]] [[era]]s of the [[geologic timescale]] (between 600 and 400 million years ago). The Iapetus Ocean was situated in the [[southern hemisphere]], between the paleocontinents of [[Laurentia]], [[Baltica]] and [[Avalonia]]. The ocean disappeared with the [[Acadian orogeny|Acadian]], [[Caledonian orogeny|Caledonian]] and [[Taconic orogeny|Taconic]] [[orogeny|orogenies]], when these three continents joined to form one big landmass called [[Euramerica]]. The "southern" Iapetus Ocean has been proposed to have closed with the [[Famatinian orogeny|Famatinian]] and Taconic orogenies, meaning a collision between [[Gondwana|Western Gondwana]] and Laurentia.
Because the Iapetus Ocean was positioned between continental masses that would at a much later time roughly form the opposite shores of the [[Atlantic Ocean]], it can be seen as a sort of precursor of the Atlantic. The Iapetus Ocean was therefore named for the [[Titan (mythology)|titan]] [[Iapetus (mythology)|Iapetus]], who in [[Greek mythology]] was the father of [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]], after whom the Atlantic Ocean was named.{{efn-ua|The name Iapetus was first used by Harland & Gayer (1972), before that the ocean was referred to as the ''Proto-Atlantic''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Banham |first1=P.H. |last2=Gibbs |first2=A.D.|last3=Hopper |first3=F.W.M. |date=1979 |title=Geological evidence in favour of a Jotunheimen Caledonian suture |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v277/n5694/abs/277289a0.html?foxtrotcallback=true |journal=Nature |volume=277 |issue= |pages=289–291 |doi=10.1038/277289a0 |access-date= }}</ref>}}
==Research history== [[File:Geological fault at Niarbyl - geograph.org.uk - 107854.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Geological fault at [[Niarbyl]]. The narrow white diagonal line near centre of picture is the only known remaining visible indication of the Iapetus Ocean]] At the start of the 20th century, American paleontologist [[Charles Doolittle Walcott|Charles Walcott]] noticed differences in early Paleozoic [[benthic zone|benthic]] [[trilobite]]s of [[Laurentia]] (such as [[Olenellidae]], the so-called "Pacific fauna"), as found in [[Scotland]] and western [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] and those of Baltica (such as [[Paradoxididae]], often called the "Atlantic fauna"), as found in the southern parts of the [[British Isles]] and eastern Newfoundland. Geologists of the early 20th century presumed that a large trough, a so-called [[geosyncline]], had existed between Scotland and England in the early Paleozoic, keeping both sides separated.<ref name="Dalziel-1997">{{Harvnb|Dalziel|1997|loc=Review: "Archetypal" and "Alternative" Paleogeographic Scenarios, pp. 18–19}}</ref>
With the development of [[plate tectonics]] in the 1960s, geologists such as [[Arthur Holmes]] and [[John Tuzo Wilson]] concluded that the Atlantic Ocean must have had a precursor before the time of [[Pangaea]]. Wilson also noticed that the Atlantic had opened at roughly the same place where its precursor ocean had closed. This led him to his [[Wilson cycle]] hypothesis.<ref name="Dalziel-1997" />
==Geodynamic history==
===Neoproterozoic origin=== In many spots in Scandinavia [[basalt]]ic [[dike (geology)|dikes]] are found with ages between 670 and 650 million years. These are interpreted as evidence that by that time, [[rift]]ing had started that would form the Iapetus Ocean.<ref name="Torsvik-etal-1996">{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Meert|Van der Voo|1996}}</ref> In [[Newfoundland and Labrador]], the [[Long Range dikes]] are also thought to have formed during the formation of the Iapetus Ocean.<ref>[http://geology.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/17/7/602 Birthdate for the lapetus Ocean? A precise U-Pb zircon and baddeleyite age for the Long Range dikes, southeast Labrador]</ref> It has been proposed that both the [[Fen Complex]] in Norway and the [[Alnö Complex]] in Sweden formed as consequence to mild [[extensional tectonics]] in the ancient continent of [[Baltica]] that followed the opening of the Iapetus Ocean.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Meert |first=Joseph G. |last2=Torsvik |first2=Trond H. |last3=Eide |first3=Elizabeth A. |last4=Dahlgren |first4=Sven |date=1998 |title=Tectonic Significance of the Fen Province, S. Norway: Constraints from Geochronology and Paleomagnetism |url=http://gondwanaresearch.com/hp/fen.pdf |journal=[[The Journal of Geology]] |volume=106 |issue= |pages=553–564 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>
The southern Iapetus Ocean opened between Laurentia and southwestern [[Gondwana]] (now South America) about 550 Ma in the [[Ediacaran]]–[[Cambrian]] transition. At the time it did so the [[Adamastor Ocean]] further east [[suture (geology)|closed]].<ref name=Gaucheretal2010>{{cite book |last=Gaucher |first=Claudio |last2=Frimmel |first2=Hartwig E. |last3=Germs |first3=J.B. |date=2010 |title=Neoproterozoic-cambrian tectonics, global change and evolution: a focus on south western Gondwana |editor-last=Gaucher |editor-first=Claudio |editor-last2=Sial |editor-first2=Alcides|editor-last3=Haverson |editor-first3=Galen |chapter=Tectonic Events and Palaeogeographic Evolution of Southwestern Gondwana in the Neoproterozoic and Cambrian|url= |location= |publisher=Elsevier |page=295–316 |isbn=}}</ref> The opening of the Iapetus Ocean probably postdates the opening of the [[Puncoviscana Formation|Puncoviscana Ocean]] with the Iapetus Ocean being separated from the Puncoviscana Ocean by the ribbon-shaped [[Arequipa-Antofalla]] [[terrane]]. However, the formation of both oceans seems unrelated.<ref name=escayolartal>{{cite journal |last=Escayola P. |first=Mónica |last2=van Staal |first2=Cees R. |last3=Davis |first3=William J. |date=2011 |title=The age and tectonic setting of the Puncoviscana Formation in northwestern Argentina: An accretionary complex related to Early Cambrian closure of the Puncoviscana Ocean and accretion of the Arequipa-Antofalla block |url= |journal=[[Journal of South American Earth Sciences]] |publisher= |volume=32 |issue= |pages=438–459 |doi= }}</ref>
===Paleozoic===
[[File:Iapetus fossil evidence EN.svg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Position of the continents after the [[Caledonian orogeny]] ([[Devonian]] to [[Permian]] times). Differences in fossil faunas on both sides of the red line (the [[Iapetus Suture]]) are evidence for the existence of an ocean between the two sides in the time before the continents were joined in the [[supercontinent]] [[Pangaea]]. <ref>Figure based on Windley (1996) and Ziegler (1990)</ref>]]
Southwest of the Iapetus, a volcanic [[island arc]] evolved from the early [[Cambrian]] (540&nbsp;million years ago) onward. This volcanic arc was formed above a [[subduction zone]] where the [[oceanic lithosphere]] of the Iapetus Ocean subducted southward under other oceanic lithosphere. From Cambrian times (about 550 million years ago) the western Iapetus Ocean began to grow progressively narrower due to this subduction. The same happened further north and east, where Avalonia and Baltica began to move towards Laurentia from the [[Ordovician]] (488-444&nbsp;million years ago) onward.<ref name="Torsvik-etal-1996" />
[[Trilobite]] [[fauna]]s of the [[continental shelf|continental shelves]] of Baltica and Laurentia are still very different in the Ordovician, but [[Silurian]] faunas show progressive mixing of species from both sides, because the continents moved closer together.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cocks|Fortey|1990}}</ref>
In the west, the Iapetus Ocean closed with the [[Taconic orogeny]] (480-430&nbsp;million years ago), when the volcanic island arc [[continental collision|collided]] with Laurentia. Some authors consider the oceanic basin south of the island arc also a part of the Iapetus, this branch closed during the later [[Acadian orogeny]], when Avalonia collided with Laurentia.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
It has been suggested that the southern Iapetus Ocean closed during a [[continental collision]] between [[Laurentia]] and [[Gondwana|Western Gondwana]] (South America). If factual the [[Taconic orogeny|Taconic orogen]] would be the northward continuation of the [[Famatinian orogeny|Famatinian orogen]] exposed in Argentina.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dalla Salda |first=Luis H.|last2=Dalziel |first2=Ian W.D.|last3=Cingolani |first3=Carlos A.|last4=Varela |first4=Ricardo |date=1992 |title=Did the Taconic Appalachians continue into southern South America? |url= |journal=[[Geology (journal)|Geology]] |publisher= |volume=20 |issue= |pages=1059–1062 |doi= 10.1130/0091-7613(1992)020<1059:dttaci>2.3.co;2}}<!--|access-date=18 September 2015--></ref>{{efn-ua|In other words, what is at present the northern end of the Famatinian orogen would have been connected with what is currently the southern end of the Taconic orogen.}}
Meanwhile, the eastern parts had closed too: the [[Tornquist Sea]] between Avalonia and Baltica already during the late Ordovician,<ref>See Torsvik & Rehnström (2003)</ref> the main branch between Baltica-Avalonia and Laurentia during the [[Grampian phase|Grampian]] and [[Scandian phase]]s of the Caledonian orogeny (440-420&nbsp;million years ago).{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
At the end of the Silurian period (c. 420 million years ago) the Iapetus Ocean had completely disappeared and the combined mass of the three continents formed the "new" continent of [[Laurasia]],<ref>See for paleogeographic reconstructions of the collisions for example Stanley (1999), p. 386; Ziegler (1990), pp. 17-19</ref> which would itself be the northern component of the singular supercontinent of [[Pangaea]].{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
